Cannes Film Festival - NOMINATED - Palme d'Or

Filmed at New Guinea Highlands, Asaro and Wahgi Valleys, upper reaches Sepik River

This picture was one of fifty Australian films selected for preservation as part of the National Film and Sound Archive of Australia's Kodak/Atlab Cinema Collection Restoration Project.

For the third time with director Lee Robinson, Chips Rafferty played his version of an Australian hero - rugged, self-reliant, resourceful, an unpolished rough diamond.

In New Guinea, a small expedition led by Steve McAllister walks towards Paradise Valley, beyond the Sepik River, where an Australian adventurer Sharkeye Kelly claims to have discovered oil. The party is an eclectic collection of different types, including a malaria-infected crocodile hunter Jeff Clayton, and a United Nations doctor Louise Demarcet. The local tribes agree to help build an airfield to provide easier exploration of the area. But Louise is attacked by a witchdoctor after she breaks a taboo and takes blood samples from the tribal leader's sick children.
